    Team News

    • Shai Gilgeous-Alexander SG, Oklahoma City Thunder

      Thunder GM Sam Presti said he wants Shai Gilgeous-Alexander to be a full-time ball-handler going forward.

      Just when you thought the hype train couldn't get any faster, Presti drops this gem. "We're really kind of clearing the way for him to expand his game, to be on the ball full time. We're putting a lot in faith in him and showing him he's a central figure to a lot of things we ultimately want to be." SGA had a massive usage rate of 31.1 without Chris Paul, Danilo Gallinari and Dennis Schroder last season and his per-minute production shot up in those minutes too. Rotoworld is all in on SGA just like last season. 

      Source: Royce Young
      Nov 30, 2020, 4:45 PM ET
      OKC wants Shai to 'be on the ball full time'
      Close
    • Frank Jackson PG, Oklahoma City Thunder

      Frank Jackson has agreed to a contract with the Thunder.

      The terms of the deal were not disclosed, but this might just be a camp invite. Even in a best-case scenario, Jackson wouldn't be anything more than the third-string PG in OKC.

      Source: Adrian Wojnarowski on Twitter
      Nov 24, 2020, 6:19 PM ET
      Frank Jackson agrees to deal with the Thunder
      Close
    • T.J. Leaf PF, Oklahoma City Thunder

      T.J. Leaf will be traded from the Pacers to the Thunder for Jalen Lecque and a future second-round pick.

      Leaf never made a reliable impression in the Pacers' rotation, averaging 8.7 minutes in his first three seasons. He'll have a much better chance to earn playing time for the rebuilding Thunder, who currently have Mike Muscala as their primary PF on the depth chart.

      Related:
      • Jalen Lecque
      • , Mike Muscala
      • , Indiana Pacers
      Source: Adrian Wojnarowski on Twitter
      Nov 22, 2020, 6:22 PM ET
      T.J. Leaf traded from Pacers to Thunder
      Close
    • Kenrich Williams SF, Oklahoma City Thunder

      Kenrich Williams has been acquired by the Thunder in the four-team deal headlined by Jrue Holiday.

      Williams, Josh Gray and Zylan Cheatham are winners in this trade, as in order for it to work financially each had to receive three-year contracts (first year guaranteed). Williams had his fantasy moments when given spot starts due to his rebounding ability, but that isn't worth using a pick on him in any league. 

      Source: Shams Charania on Twitter
      Nov 22, 2020, 2:39 PM ET
      Kenrich Williams headed to Oklahoma City in trade
      Close
    • Zylan Cheatham SF, Oklahoma City Thunder

      Zylan Cheatham has been sent to Oklahoma City as part of the four-team trade headlined by Jrue Holiday. 

      Cheatham barely played during his time with the Pelicans, so he may have a shot at earning some minutes in Oklahoma City as the Thunder rebuild. But it won't be enough to make him a viable option in any format.

      Source: Shams Charania on Twitter
      Nov 22, 2020, 2:37 PM ET
      Zylan Cheatham traded to OKC in Holiday deal
      Close
    • Josh Gray PG, Oklahoma City Thunder

      Josh Gray has been traded to Oklahoma City as part of the four-team deal headlined by Jrue Holiday. 

      Gray wasn't particularly valuable as a fantasy option, as he was on a two-way contract last season. Even with the change of scenery that will remain the case.

      Source: Shams Charania on Twitter
      Nov 22, 2020, 1:44 PM ET
      Josh Gray sent to OKC in Jrue Holiday trade
      Close
    • Darius Miller SF, Oklahoma City Thunder

      Darius Miller has been traded to the Thunder as part of the Steven Adams deal.

      The Thunder will also be snagging a 2023 protected first-round pick from Denver, a 2023 second-round selection from Charlotte and a 2024 second-round pick from Washington. As for Miller, he tore his Achilles back in August of 2019, and it remains unclear if he'll be ready for the start of the 2020-21 season. 

      Source: Adrian Wojnarowski on Twitter
      Nov 21, 2020, 10:02 AM ET
      Darius Miller traded to the Thunder
      Close
    • George Hill PG, Oklahoma City Thunder

      George Hill and Darius Miller will be sent to the Thunder as part of the four-team trade involving Steven Adams.

      Hill gets flipped for a second time, and it wouldn't be shocking to see Oklahoma City move him again for some more draft picks. Even if Hill and Miller stick with the Thunder, we wouldn't anticipate them holding much fantasy value, as Hill is going into his age-34 season and Miller has always been irrelevant.

      Source: Adrian Wojnarowski on Twitter
      Nov 21, 2020, 9:58 AM ET
      George Hill & Darius Miller headed to the Thunder
      Close
    • Justin Jackson SF, Oklahoma City Thunder

      Justin Jackson has been traded to the Thunder as part of a three-team deal, according to ESPN's Adrian Wojnarowski.

      The Thunder are hoovering up draft picks and Jackson may not be part of their plans, but there are worse landing spots for fantasy purposes. The former No. 15 pick hasn't found much success in three seasons, peaking at 8.2 points and 48.4% shooting with Dallas last year, and he regressed with sub-40% shooting last year. He'll be safe to leave on the waiver wire no matter which jersey he's wearing.

      Source: Adrian Wojnarowski on Twitter
      Nov 21, 2020, 1:22 AM ET
      Justin Jackson traded to OKC in three-team deal
      Close
    • Trevor Ariza SF, Oklahoma City Thunder

      Trevor Ariza has been traded from the Pistons to the Thunder as part of a three-team deal on Friday.

      A previous report had Ariza headed to Dallas, but he will in fact be joining the Thunder. In the span of five days, Ariza was traded from the Blazers to the Rockets to the Pistons to the Thunder. And given OKC's all-out rebuild that's underway, Ariza could be on the move again before long. No matter where he lands, the 16-year veteran should fill his usual 3-and-D role -- nearly 65% of his shot attempts last season were 3-pointers. He's unlikely to earn the 33.1 per game he averaged last year no matter where he's playing, though, so he's best viewed as a waiver-wire source of triples and steals.

      Source: Adrian Wojnarowski on Twitter
      Nov 21, 2020, 1:21 AM ET
      Trevor Ariza traded (again) from Detroit to OKC
      Close

    • Luguentz Dort PG, Oklahoma City Thunder

      Luguentz Dort erupted for a career-high 30 points on Wednesday, making 10-of-21 shots with six 3-pointers, four rebounds, one assist and one block in 35 minutes.

      Dort's defense against James Harden has given him a national reputation, but his offense was the story tonight. He had a game-high 18 points with five minutes left in the second quarter, taking full advantage of the fact that Houston's defense completely ignored him. It was a logical strategy after he shot a combined 12-of-46 in the first four games of this series, including 7-of-38 from deep (18.4%). He scored double-digit points only seven times during the regular season, and his previous high was 23 points on Jan. 29, so fantasy managers should probably view this as a small-sample-size aberration. 

      Sep 3, 2020, 12:27 AM ET
      Luguentz Dort scores career-high 30 points in loss
      Close
    • Shai Gilgeous-Alexander SG, Oklahoma City Thunder

      Shai Gilgeous-Alexander shot 6-of-11 from the field for 19 points on Wednesday, adding four assists, three rebounds, three 3-pointers and a pair of steals in 41 minutes.

      SGA came in averaging 15.8 points, 5.7 boards, 4.2 dimes and 1.8 threes in the playoffs. That's 3.2 points lower than his regular-season average, but his team-first attitude was on full display tonight. He and Chris Paul each took a modest 11 shots, setting up easier looks for teammates Lu Dort (10-of-21 shooting) and Dennis Schroder (5-of-17). The Thunder will bow out after the first round, but they weren't expected to make the playoffs and yet they took the Rockets to Game 7. Danilo Gallinari and Nerlens Noel are unrestricted free agents, but the rest of OKC's core is under contract. It'll be fascinating to see how much the team's ownership is willing to invest with a win-now approach.

      Related:
      • Luguentz Dort
      • , Dennis Schroder
      • , Chris Paul
      Sep 3, 2020, 12:25 AM ET
      Shai Gilgeous-Alexander posts 19/4/3/3/2 in defeat

    • Luguentz Dort PG, Oklahoma City Thunder

      Lu Dort bounced back from a tough Game 5 to hit 5-of-9 shots and two huge 3-pointers for 13 points, three rebounds, one assist, one steal, one block and five turnovers in Monday's 104-100 win to force a Game 7 on Wednesday.

      Dort hit just 3-of-16 shots for six points in a Game 5 blowout loss and he had hit just 12-of-46 shots in his previous four games in this series. Dort's defense is always good and he came through on the offensive end tonight, hitting 5-of-9 shots. His back-to-back 3-pointers helped the Thunder to an 8-0 run and kept them in the game, giving his team a 77-75 lead late in the third quarter. It will be interesting to see if Dort can keep it going in a pressure-packed Game 7 on Wednesday. In addition to Dort, Darius Bazley came through with eight points, nine rebounds and a 3-pointer in the win. 

      Related:
      • Darius Bazley
      Sep 1, 2020, 12:02 AM ET
      Lu Dort hits a couple big 3-pointers in win
